<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="110" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="25.[136,1452,158,904]" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,345,374,400]" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">Distribution:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scopoli" authorityYear="1772" box="[373,603,374,400]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Callitriche" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="25" pageNumber="110" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="stagnalis">
<emphasis box="[373,603,374,400]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">Callitriche stagnalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is native to Europe, from the Azores to 
<collectingCountry box="[1053,1135,374,400]" name="Iceland" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">Iceland</collectingCountry>
and east to the western side of the Ural Mountains in 
<collectingCountry box="[414,489,410,436]" name="Russia" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">Russia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Lansdown, R. V." box="[502,700,410,437]" pageId="25" pageNumber="110" pagination="354 - 361" refId="ref29815" refString="Lansdown, R. V. (2006 a) The genus Callitriche (Callitrichaceae) in Asia. Novon 16: 354 - 361. https: // doi. org / 10.3417 / 1055 - 3177 (2006) 16 [354: TGCCIA] 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2006">Lansdown 2006a</bibRefCitation>
). It also occurs as an alien (naturalised) in North America (
<bibRefCitation author="Philbrick, C. T. &amp; Aakjar Jr., R. A. &amp; Stuckey, R. L." pageId="25" pageNumber="110" pagination="25 - 38" refId="ref30524" refString="Philbrick, C. T., Aakjar Jr., R. A. &amp; Stuckey, R. L. (1998) Invasion and spread of Callitriche stagnalis (Callitrichaceae) in North America. Rhodora 100: 25 - 38." type="journal article" year="1998">
Philbrick 
<emphasis box="[136,194,446,472]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">et al.</emphasis>
1998
</bibRefCitation>
), 
<collectingCountry box="[281,384,446,472]" name="Australia" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">Australia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Orchard, A. E." box="[400,562,446,472]" pageId="25" pageNumber="110" pagination="191 - 194" refId="ref30495" refString="Orchard, A. E. (1980) Callitriche (Callitrichaceae) in South Australia. Journal of the Adelaide Botanic Garden 2: 191 - 194." type="journal article" year="1980">Orchard 1980</bibRefCitation>
), 
<collectingCountry box="[583,758,446,473]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[815,966,446,473]" name="New Zealand" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Mason, R." box="[983,1129,446,473]" pageId="25" pageNumber="110" pagination="295 - 327" refId="ref30384" refString="Mason, R. (1959) Callitriche in New Zealand and Australia. Australian Journal of Botany 7: 295 - 327. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / BT 9590295" type="journal article" year="1959">Mason 1959</bibRefCitation>
). Two specimens are known from South America, one from 
<collectingRegion box="[488,671,482,508]" country="Chile" name="Biobio" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">Biobío Province</collectingRegion>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[706,767,482,508]" name="Chile" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">Chile</collectingCountry>
and one from the 
<collectingCountry box="[971,1159,482,508]" name="Falkland Islands" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">Falkland Islands</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[136,1452,158,904]" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,265,518,544]" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">Notes:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scopoli" authorityYear="1772" box="[294,524,518,544]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Callitriche" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="25" pageNumber="110" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="stagnalis">
<emphasis box="[294,524,518,544]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">Callitriche stagnalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was reported in error from 
<collectingCountry box="[843,914,518,544]" name="Brazil" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, but recognised as occurring as a non-native in 
<collectingCountry box="[136,197,554,580]" name="Chile" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">Chile</collectingCountry>
and the 
<collectingCountry box="[289,471,554,580]" name="Falkland Islands" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">Falkland Islands</collectingCountry>
(Lansdown &amp; Hassemer 2018). It can be distinguished from all other 
<taxonomicName box="[1243,1451,554,580]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Callitriche" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="25" pageNumber="110" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[1243,1364,554,580]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">Callitriche</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
in the region bY the large fruit (&gt; 
<quantity box="[511,576,590,617]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="25" pageNumber="110" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
diameter), long stYle (≤ 
<quantity box="[852,917,590,617]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="25" pageNumber="110" unit="mm" value="6.0">6 mm</quantity>
long) and long filament (≤ 
<quantity box="[1226,1305,590,617]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="25" pageNumber="110" unit="mm" value="16.0">16 mm</quantity>
long).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[136,1452,158,904]" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,440,626,652]" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">Conservation status:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scopoli" authorityYear="1772" box="[468,702,626,652]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Callitriche" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="25" pageNumber="110" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="stagnalis">
<emphasis box="[468,702,626,652]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">Callitriche stagnalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is classed as Least Concern (LC) because it is widespread and abundant through much of its native range.
</paragraph>
